@node Copyrights "How ModAns may be spread"

ModAns is FreeWare, it is NOT in the Public Domain. That means that you
may use and spread ModAns freely. It is not permitted to sell it for
unreasonable prices. "Unreasonable" means much more than eg disks and
distribution costs.
  Neither is it permitted to spread ModAns modified. All the files should
be present and they should be in their original state.
@endnode
@node Intro "What is ModAns?"

First of all, ModAns requires AmigaOS 2.0 and should work fine with all
versions above that.

You could say that ModAns, just like before, is an answering machine.
That is, however, not the entire truth. Actually it is some code to use
the serial.device bundled with an ARexx interface.

With ModAns comes an ARexx program to use it just like before, as an
answering machine. I guess this will be the most common use of ModAns.
There are some other possibilities though. Theoretically you could write
a little BBS program. Another usage is to keep count of how many calls
you have recieved when you have been away for a while. (Once I wrote an
NComm script for a guy that did just that. :-)

When ModAns is started (and there is no startup script to be run) you get
in a direct mode with the modem. In this mode ModAns can be used as a very
simple (and not very fast) terminal program.
  To do something else an ARexx program has to be started. In order to
make the programs work  you have tell which port the program should talk
to. If no port name is stated with the @{"PORTNAME" link PortName} option and there is
only one ModAns running the name of the port is "MODANS.0". This can also
be found in the titlebar of the window.

You have to add this line in the beginning of the program:

address MODANS.0
@endnode
@node Quick "Quick Start"

To get a working answering machine you have to do two things:

  1) @{"Configure" link Config} ModAns to work with your modem.

  2a) If you are using Shell, set the @{"STARTUP" link Startup} option to
      @{"Mailbox" link Mailbox}.rexx on the command line.

       ModAns STARTUP Work:ModAns/MailBox.rexx

      Note that it must be an absolute path.


  2b) From Workbench, set the tooltype @{"STARTUP" link Startup} to the file
      @{"MailBox" link MailBox}.rexx.

       STARTUP=Work:ModAns/MailBox.rexx

      Note that it must be an absolute path.
@endnode
@node Config "Configuration"

To get ModAns to work with your modem you have to fill in the file
ModAns.cfg. This file must then be present in the current directory
when ModAns is started. (From Workbench this is the same drawer where
ModAns is.) If no file is found in the current directory ModAns also
looks in S:.
  With the @{"SETTINGS" link Settings} option you can explicit tell ModAns where too
look for the configuration file.

Every line i ModAns.cfg consists of a keyword, an equality sign ('=')
and the the actual configuration string. Note that there must be no
space neither before nor after the '=' and that the keywords must be
be in the right order. You can put comments between the lines as long
as they doesn't match any keyword.

The different keywords are:

      @{"INITSTRING" link InitString}
      @{"ANSWERSTRING" link AnswerString}
      @{"HANGUPSTRING" link HangupString}
      @{"HIGHBAUDRATE" link HighBaudrate}
      @{"LOCK" link Lock}
      @{"DEVICE" link Device}
      @{"UNIT" link Unit}
      @{"HELPFILE" link MAHelpFile}
@endnode
@node Shell "To start ModAns from Shell"

ModAns can be started from anywhere. There is no demand to be in the right
right directory. You have to tell ModAns where to find @{"ModAns.cfg" link Config} if
it's not in the current directory or S:. This can be accomplished with the
@{"SETTINGS" link Settings} option.

The command template is
@{"SETTINGS" link Settings}/K,@{"PUBSCREEN" link PubScreen}/K,@{"STARTUP" link Startup}/K,@{"PORTNAME" link PortName}/K,@{"NOGUI" link NoGui}/S
@{"TOP" link Coords}/N,@{"LEFT" link Coords}/N,@{"HEIGHT" link Coords}/N,@{"WIDTH" link Coords}/N

The different options can be used in arbitrary order. E.g:

ModAns STARTUP MyHack.rexx NOGUI
ModAns PUBSCREEN Shell PORTNAME ModAnsPort
ModAns NOGUI SETTINGS MySettings.cfg STARTUP BBS.rexx
@endnode
@node WB "To start ModAns from Workbench"

All you have to do to start ModAns is to doubble click its icon.
@{"ModAns.cfg" link Config} is probably in the the same drawer as ModAns itself so you
shuoldn't have to worry about that.

There are differnt tooltypes that can be given as options to ModAns. To
change the tooltypes, mark the ModAns icon and select Information from
the Workbench menu.

     @{"SETTINGS" link Settings}
     @{"PUBSCREEN" link PubScreen}
     @{"STARTUP" link Startup}
     @{"PORTNAME" link PortName}
     @{"NOGUI" link NoGui}
     @{"TOP" link Coords}, @{"LEFT" link Coords}, @{"HEIGHT" link Coords} and @{"WIDTH" link Coords}

Some examples of the usage of the tooltypes is:

PUBSCREEN=Shell
NOGUI
PORTNAME=MODANSPORT
@endnode
@node History "What has happened through the yaers."

2.0 (94-03-10)
This is the fourth version of ModAns. The only thing it has in common
with the former versions is the name and the idea. Virtually all the
code is rewritten and the concept is the new. This is why I don't
include bugfixes and stuff for the former versions.

1.20 (91-06-21)

1.15 (91-04-04)

1.1  (91-??-??)
@endnode
@node Startup "The STARTUP option"

This tells ModAns which ARexx program it should launch automatically
on startup. Since it is ARexx, not ModAns, that launches the program
it has to have a full path. That is if it is not in Rexx:.

Due to what I think is a bug in ARexx the programs do not automatically
get the right default address. You have to do this explicit with the
address command.
@endnode
@node Settings "The SETTINGS option"

This tells which @{"configuration file" link Config} ModAns should use. It can be both
an absolut or a relative path. If this file is not found ModAns tries to
use ModAns.cfg in the current directory. If there is no such file either
it tries with S:ModAns.cfg.
@endnode
@node PubScreen "Parametern PUBSCREEN"

This tells which public screen ModAns should open it's window on.
If this option not is present, the default public screen is used.
This is normally the Workbench screen.
@endnode
@node PortName "Parametern PORTNAME"

This tells which name the ARexx port should have. If this option not is
present "MODANS.0" will be used for the first ModAns running. If ModAns
is started several times it will use "MODANS.1", "MODANS.2" etc. Which
name that is actually used can be found in the titlebar of the window.

It is preffered that the name is in capitals only. This because the line

address MinPort

becomes "address MINPORT" before it is executed. If there is lower case
letters in the name you have to write:

address 'MinPort'
@endnode
@node Coords "The options TOP, LEFT, HEIGHT and WIDTH"

This tells ModAns where to put its window on the screen and how big it
should be. The defaults are TOP=10, LEFT=0, HEIGHT=200 and WIDTH=640.
@endnode
@node NoGui "The NOGUI option"

This tells ModAns not to open any window. The only way to communicate
with ModAns is through @{"ARexx" link ARexx}.

The window can later be opened again with the ARexx command @{"WINDOW" link Window}.
@endnode
@node InitString "The INITSTRING keyword"

This tells which AT command that makes the modem ready to recieve a call.
Exactly what should be written here depends on the type of modem. Take a
look in the manual of your modem if you run into problems.

Some commands that you might want to use are:

E      ATE1 turns the modem's echo on while ATE0 turns it off. In direct
       mode you have to have it on to see what commands you give to the
       modem. In a Arexx program you probably want to have it turned off.

S0=0   S0 tells the modem how many RING signals it should wait before
       it answers. (0 means that it doesn't answer at all.) If you at the
       keyword @{"ANSWERSTRING" link AnswerString} tell ModAns to deal with the answering S0
       should be set to 0. If you want to use the modem's built in
       auto answer function you should set S0 to a positive value. (1 is
       the best in most cases.)

M      ATM0 turns the modem's speaker off while ATM1 turns it on. With
       ATL you can set the volume.

Q      Q0 tells the modem to answer with OK (or ERROR) when a command is
       given. This must be used.

With high speed modems you have to enable handshaking (RTS/CTS) and lock
the speed between the computer and the modem. Again, look in your modem's
manual.

Note that INITSTRING not is used directly when ModAns is started but when
the ARexx command @{"WAITCONNECT" link WaitConnect} is called.
@endnode
@node AnswerString "The ANSWERSTRING keyword"

This tells what command to use to make the modem answer. On virtually
every modem this is ATA. When ANSWERSTRING is set to "ATA" ModAns will
try to answer when somebody calls. The modem's built in auto answer must
then be disabled. This is done with ATS0=0 in @{"INISTRING" link InitString}.

If you want to use the modem's built in auto answer you set this to a
dash ('-'). The former is however preffered.
@endnode
@node HangupString "The HANGUPSTRING keyword"

This tells which command that makes the modem hang up. On virtually every
modem this is ATH. Before ATH is sent ModAns sends three plus signs ("+++")
to get the modem in command mode.

A somewhat safer way to hang up is to close the connection to the modem
for a short while. The modem should then hang up. On some modems you
to tell it to do so with a special AT command. Take a look in the manual
of your modem.
  To use this safer way, set HANGUPSTRING to a dash ('-') instead of ATH.
@endnode
@node HighBaudrate "The HIGHBAUDRATE keyword"

This tells which speed is the highest the modem can communicate with
the computer. For normal 2400 bps modems this is 2400. For high speed
modems you use a higher rate than the actual speed over the telephone line.
19200 and 38400 are common speeds for this. You should then also lock the
speed with the keyword @{"LOCK" link Lock}.
@endnode
@node Lock "The LOCK keyword"

Set this to YES if the speed between the computer and the modem should be
locked and NO if that is not tha case. For highspeed modems you should
lock the speed in a speed that is higher than the actual rate on the
telephone line.

Is this is set to NO ModAns will check the CONNECT-message for the
connection rate and set the rate between the computer and the modem to
this. (This is however only done when useing the ARexx command @{"WAITCONNECT" link WaitConnect}.
If a connection is made in direct mode you are responsible for getting the
speed right with the ARexx command @{"BAUD" link Baud}.)
@endnode
@node Device "The DEVICE keyword"

This tells which device the modem is connected to. Normally this is the
internal serial port and this should the be set to "serial.device".
Other possibilities are:

Supra 2400zi internal modem modem0.device
ASDG Dual Serial Board      siosbx.device
Multiface Card              duart.device
@endnode
@node Unit "The UNIT keyword"

This tells which unit number at the device that is used. For the internal
serial port this is 0. For Supra 2400zi this is also 0. For serial boards
this depends on which port the modem is connected to. Check your manual.
@endnode
@node MAHelpFile "The HELPFILE keyword"

This tells which text file that should be used when the user issues the
command '!?' inside the editor. (The editor is started with the ARexx
command @{"EDITTEXT" link EditText}.) This field gives an opportunity
to translate the file into different languages.
@endnode
@node ARexx "How to controll ModAns from ARexx"

ModAns depends entirely on ARexx. Without ARexx ModAns is not very useful.

The ARexx port is named MODANS.0 for the first ModAns running. For
subsequent ModAns the name becomes MODANS.1, MODANS.2 etc. You can also
define your own name using the @{"PORTNAME" link PortName} option.

ModAns is always prepared to recieve an ARexx command. Some command take
a while to execute, e.g @{"WAITCONNECT" link WaitConnect}. If another command comes
before it is done it will be cancelled and the new one will be executed
instead.

If you use the @{"STARTUP" link Startup} option that program will be automatically
launched when ModAns starts. This is however nothing you have to do.
You can as well start ModAns without any startup program and run
a ARexx program later or just give simple commands from Shell.

The ARexx commands avaliable are:

@{"BAUD" link Baud}          Sets the baudrate for the serial port.
@{"DUPLEX" link Duplex}        Sets full or half duplex.
@{"EDITTEXT" link EditText}      Edits a text and saves it as ASCII.
@{"GETSTRING" link GetString}     Gets a string.
@{"HANGUP" link Hangup}        Hangs up.
@{"INITMODEM" link InitModem}     Sends an AT command to the modem.
@{"QUIT" link Quit}          Quits ModAns.
@{"SEND" link Send}          Sends a string.
@{"SENDTEXTFILE" link SendTextFile}  Sends a text file.
@{"WAITCONNECT" link WaitConnect}   Waits for a connection.
@{"WINDOW" link Window}        Open, closes or changes the window.


With ModAns comes a ready-to-run program called @{"MailBox" link MailBox}. This program
emulates the function of ModAns v1.x.

When you have written an ARexx program you probably want to test it.
A very suitable program for this is nullmodem.device, written by Iain
Hibbert. It emulates a modem so you can let two programs communicate
just like they were using real modems when they actually run in the
very same computer.
In one end you can start ModAns and in the other a terminal program. (Or
why not ModAns in direct mode..)
@endnode
@node Baud "The ARexx command BAUD"

BAUD - Sets the baudrate for the serial port.

Synopsis: BAUD /N

The only option is an integer that tells which speed that is to be set.
There is no error checking that this is a sensible value and the hardware
likes it.
The speed can be changed even if @{"LOCK" link Lock} is YES in @{"ModAns.cfg" link Config}.

Results: None

Example: BAUD 2400
@endnode
@node Duplex "The ARexx command DUPLEX"}

DUPLEX - Sets full or half duplex.

Synopsis: DUPLEX FULL/S,HALF/S

The only actual effect of the duplex setting is in direct mode. In full
duplex the things written in the window is only sent to the modem. In half
duplex it is both sent to the modem and printed in the window.

Reults: Error code 10 if neither HALF nor FULL is stated.

Example: DUPLEX HALF
         DUPLEX FULL
@endnode
@node EditText "The ARexx command EDITTEXT"

EDITTEXT - Edits a text and saves it as ASCII.

Synopsis: EDITTEXT /A

The option, which must be stated, is a file name where the edited text
should be saved. If this file already exists when the editor is started
it will be loaded and you can continue editing.

In the editor commands can be issued by entering an exclamation mark as
the first character on the line, followed by a command character. The
avaliable commands are:

!c /N (change) Changes the stated line. Ctrl-F gives one character at the
               time and Ctrl-R gives the rest of the line.

!r    (read)   Shows the entire text.

!q    (quit)   Cancel the editor without saving the text.

!s    (save)   Saves the text and leaves the editor.

!?    (help)   Shows the helpfile as stated in @{"HELPFILE" link MAHelpFile}.

Results:
Error codes: 5  - The user cancelled the editor.
             20 - The text could not be saved.
             30 - The user did hangup in the editor. The text i saved.
             40 - The user did hangup and the text could not be saved.

Examples: EDITTEXT Mytext.txt
          EDITTEXT Work:AnotherText.txt
@endnode
@node GetString "The ARexx command GETSTRING"

GETSTRING - Gets a string.

Synopsis: GETSTRING /N,NOECHO/S

If an integer is given, this is the maximum number of characters that
may be typed. Default is 50.
NOECHO tells that nothing will be echoed back to the user. The user will
not see what he is writing.

Results:
Error codes: 5  - GetString was interuupted by another ARexx command.
             20 - ModAns could not allocate memory for the result string.
             30 - The user did hangup.

The string is returned in the RESULT variable.

Example: GETSTRING 35
         GETSTRING 10 NOECHO
@endnode
@node Hangup "The ARexx command HANGUP"

HANGUP - Hang up

Synopsis: HANGUP

The modem is hanged up as stated in @{"ModAns.cfg" link Config}.

Reults: None

Example: HANGUP
@endnode
@node InitModem "The ARexx command INITMODEM"

INITMODEM - Sends an AT command to the modem.

Synopsis: INITMODEM /A

The command does not necesarily have to begin with AT. ModAns will however
wait for either OK or ERROR from the modem.

Results: None

Example: INITMODEM ATM1
@endnode
@node Quit "The ARexx command QUIT"

QUIT - Quits ModAns

Synsopsis: QUIT

Results: None

Example: QUIT
@endnode
@node Send "The ARexx command SEND"

SEND - Sends a string.

Synsopsis: SEND /A

Results: None

Example: SEND 'Hello there!'
@endnode
@node SendTextFile "The ARexx command SENDTEXTFILE"

SENDTEXTFILE - Sends a text file.

Synsopsis: SENDTEXTFILE /A

Results: None

Example: SENDTEXTFILE Work:Mytext.txt
@endnode
@node WaitConnect "The ARexx command WAITCONNECT"

WAITCONNECT - Wait for a connection

Synsopsis: WAITCONNECT DEBUG/S

The DEBUG option doesn't actually do very much. The only thing is that
ModAns writes "Waiting for connection" when WAITCONNECT is called.

WAITCONNECT initializes the modem with the string given in @{"INITSTRING" link InitString}.
It then waits for a RING from the modem if it is said to do so in
@{"ANSWERSTRING" link AnswerString}. When it recognizes a CONNECT-message
it will change the serial speed to the speed of the message if @{"LOCK" link Lock} is
set to NO. After that it will return.

Results: None

Example: WAITCONNECT DEBUG
@endnode
@node Window "The ARexx command WINDOW"

WINDOW - Open, closes or changes the window

Synopsis: WINDOW OPEN/S,CLOSE/S,ACTIVATE/S,MIN/S,MAX/S,FRONT/S,BACK/S

OPEN and CLOSE opens and closes the window respectively.
ACTIVATE makes the window the active one.
MIN and MAX makes the window as small and as big as possible respectively.
FRONT and BACK sends the window to the front and to the back respectively.

Results: None

Example: WINDOW OPEN ACTIVATE
         WINDOW FRONT MAX
@endnode
@node MailBox "ARexx-programmet MailBox"

The program MailBox that comes with ModAns tries to emulate the earlier
versions (1.x).

When somebody calls ot first shows the text Login.txt. After that the user
is asked if he wants to leave a massage or not. If he wants to a text is
edited that will be saved as <date>_<time> in the current directory.
After that the text Logout.txt is showed and the line is hanged up.
@endnode
